@article{Williams1998,
  abstract = {Many numerical models for flows of immiscible fluids bounded by topologically complex interfaces possessing surface tension are based on an Eulerian formulation of the equations of motion. In these models the location of the interface is usually represented by a scalar function f , sometimes referred to as a color function, that varies monotonically from one constant value to another through the interface. This transition region is a thin band along the interface within which surface tension forces are applied in continuum surface tension (CST) models. The function f can be regarded as a numerical approximation to the characteristic function associated with the interface. Although widely used, many CST models do not accurately approximate interface topology such as unit normal and mean curvature. These inaccuracies arise because of difficulties in approximating the spatial derivatives of the function f in the transition region. Accurate representations of the Dirac delta function are also needed to formulate the force due to surface tension in the transition region. Here we study the role of convolving the funciton f with a smooth, radially-symmetric kernel to improve estimates to the interface topology. In particular, we introduce a new kernel that results in a better estimation to the spatial derivatives of f and present a hybrid convolution-finite difference technique to estimate interface curvatures. Our CST algorithm generates better than second-order accurate approximations to the curvature of circular and spherical interfaces. It also mitigates the numerically-induced "parasitic currents' in computations of a spherical drop in static equilibrium.},
